er\nnoon. The Matson freighter Hilonian left\nHilo for San Francisco on Wednesday\nlast.\nThe steamer Manna Loa will sail for\nKona and Kan at noon today. Her\ncargo will consist tf 110 tons of fcr-\ntilizer and general merchandise.\nThe steamer Helene arrived yester-\n?ort at seven-thirty o clock, and cnfrnr 7- hlKU, nf ttl. a(1\n9 pliability is she will not disap- j twelve calves from the Parker Ranch.\na mybojy, for she is never short. pui.ser McKenz.e reiorted fine weath\nmi. She has ninety-four cabin er 0D Hamakua.\nfsm and 2807 tons o\"f cargo. j\n3e Siberia of the Pacific Mail line i nn. r nrrr\nMve Mondav with Tasseneers and NA I IUN AL. UULr WCC I\n\"Btfroni the Orient. She will rrob-\n'afl Monday afternoon, unless she\ntoo late to be dispatched then.\neaae will leave Tuesday morn-\nMore Subsidy for T. K, K.\n'E0, Angnst lO.-The Tokyo\non!d make some reserve in\ntt eiTICB OP THE U KITED\n,4IB8 WBATHES BUREAU.\n.Thursday, August 25, 1910.\nCOMES NEXT MONTH\nTStKMO.\nI\nfl oj\n-its\nWIND\nTournament to Award Amateur\nChampionship Medals Starts\non 12th cf September.\n9.- The\n5\n4 a\nn\nI i\n'Mi,!\n\"Ms1\na.:.\nttJ\n72\n74\nli\n't\nit\n86\n73\n50 .OC; 77 i SB\nj .0C 6S S SE\n?S j .CS; 89 4 j SK\nJ8 is' 72 5 j se\n'8 j .17 63 4 N E 1\n,s W K 4 j SI io\n79 I T 82 3 PR I S\n79 .CI 71 2 sk 9\n13 -02 85 7 j s E 9\n18 J .Oi, Hs 2 j -s j 7\ni 140 S2 5 I SB i 7\n'5 j .14 72 j5 I Ng\"\nB. STuCKMAN,\n8ection Direct r.\n5J?TO A2TD MOON.\nThe issuing of the official program\nfor the amateur championship of the\nUnited States Golf Association, to be\nheld over the links of the Country Club\nof Brookline, Massachusetts, is now\nattracting the attention of golfers.\nexact dates are September 12 to\n17 inclusive. This competition is open\nto all golfers who belong to clubs which\nare members of the United States Golf\nAssociation and to those foreigners\nvisiting the United States who may be\ninvited by the executive committee of\nthe association. The Havemeyer cup\nf.nd four medals will be competed for\nunder the association rules.\nAccording to the conditions the win\ni.er of the conijttition will be known\nas the champion amateur golfer for fh?\nvear and the cup shall be held for that\nvear bv the club from which the winner\nhall i'uve entered. He will receive a\na\nists bron.e nu-r.a.s.\na special r lor\nthe\nst eore\nj qualifying round.\nI will\n18i IIS1(, li\nil-i4'1i,n-'\n1 8.8'\n1.5-\n:.!cj\nW-K;0.18 5.re.21 fe'.lrt\nI\nI\" 12 5. 42 B .20 6.?3\n'P.m.' I\n0 CO u.i6 5.42 6.iit 9 34\na.m.j i i i\nO.iti 1.24 s ti id i\n1 17\ni\n1.24 V42 6 lit 1,\n8Xrt.\"..43e.:sl0.5H\n5. Si 5.4-1 P.17 J1.51\nold !iu-dal outrght, the runner-up\nilver medal, and the other semi-final-\nThere will a:o no\nthe player making\nin the tlurty-six-iioie\nThe method of play-\nbe the same tnis year as lasr.\nIn the event of a tie or ties ior tie\nlast T.lace on Moc lav or Tuesday morn\ning, the contesa::s so tied shall\ntinue to pir.v until one of them\nl,.,v. tri.ine.l a. lead bv a stroke at\nhole. Where\nhalved match\ntin ue to play\nhave won a\nthe winner of\nThis will be\ntorv of A merle:. n g\nmore spacious and more luxurious of\nfices downtown or elsewhere.\nDrake hasn't anything to say in the\npremises beyond the plain assertion\nthat Superintendent of Public Works\nMarston Campbell politely informed\nhim that his space was more valuable\nto the Territory than is hi business\nas chief of the internal revenue. Camp\nbell, of course, did not use such words,\nmereiv notifying Drake that the Ter\nritory, or the public works, which is\na laige slice of the territorial govern\nment, had other use for the quarters\nnow occupied by Drake than allowing\nthe United States to have any depart\nment sheltered in the artistic and im\nposing pile known as the executive\nbuilding, but still referred to by many\nas \"the palace.\"\nDrake is paying $40 a month for a\nfew box-like rooms which have been\nturned into headquarters for the inter\nnal revenue representatives. It would\ncost at least $150 a month for Drake\nto take up quarters outside the execu\ntive building. If \"Washington approves\nthe increased expense, then well and\ngood, and Drake will move and Camp\nbell can put in hydrogra pliers, typo\ngraphers, legislative committees or any\none else for whom there is no room\nelsewhere. But if Washington does not\napprove the additional expenditure,\nthen there is likely to be resistance\nto having to move out.\nThere seems to be something of an\nattitude on the part of the Territory to\nthrow out federal offices from the execu\ntive building. The throne room and the j\nsenate chamber may go unoccupied ex\ncept by furnitnre for months on months,\nand rooms in the basement can be used i\nfor the storage of books and records i\nof the public works department and\nthe auditor s bureau, but the internal\nrevenue man shall have no where to\nlav his head.\nCampbell wants to provide downstairs\nrooms for the work of legislative com- j\nmittees and he plans tearing down the j\nunsightly veranda committee rooms\nerected during the last gathering of the j\nsolons. It is remarked that it is not\nthe failst of the' Territory if Hawaii\ndo.\"s not happen to have a federal J\nbuilding in which Drake might be ac-\ncommodated, and there is perhaps a\ntendency to draw Washington's atfen-I\ntion to the need of a federal building\nbv making an impressive exhibition of J\nthe idea that there is not enough room\ni -n- j? n it\nm the executive miiioisig nr an uit;\nterritorial departments, much less\nany department of Uncle Sam.\nFIDELITY OR SURETY\nWe Execute Either\nCon tr vtors A dministra tors\nTreasurers Cashiers Clerks\nEtc., Etc.\nDON'T TRUST TO LUCK!\nTRENT TRUST CO., LTD.\nTouring Car, demi-tonneau, or Runabout, Price S1700 f. o. b. Detroit.\nImportant Improvements in 191 1\nINCEEASED POWER.\nCylinder bore increased from 4'i\ninches to AV-2 inches. This, with\nmore efficient carbureter, (Special\nSchebler) which is water-jacketed,\neffects a material increase in power.\nPiston stroke, inches.\nThe four cylinders are cast sin\ngly, with copper jackets applied, re\ntaining the exclusive Cadillac fea\ntures throughout. Horsepower, A.\nL. A. M. Tating, 32.4.\nINCREASED COMFORT.\nWheelbase increased from 110 to\n116 inches, making the car ride\nmore easily than ever.\nIMPROVED APPEARANCE.\nDouble drop frame, 2-inch drop,\nwhich makes car set lower, and this\nwith the larger hood and more\nroomy tonneau greatly improves the\nappearance.\nLARGE RADIATOR.\nThe radiator is larger, hence has\ngreater cooling capacity. This is\nnotwithstanding the fact tbat the\nCadillac was never deficient in that\nrespect.\nTIMKEN AXLE.\nFull floating type Timken roller\nbearing rear axle. This is the same\naxle as used on a number of Amer\nica's highest priced cars.\nLARGER BRAKE DRUMS.\nLarger brake drums giving great\nly increased efficiency. Contracting\nand expanding double acting brakes,\nboth equalized.\nTWO IGNITION SYSTEMS.\nTwo complete and independent\nignition systems, each with its own\nset of spark plugs. The two igni\ntion systems consist of Bosch high\ntension magneto and the new and\nimproved Delco system with single\nunit coil, high tension distributor\nand controlling relay. Either sys\ntem alone is efficient for operating\nthe car.\nENCLOSED WIRING.\nAll electrical wiring enclosed in\ncopper tubes.\nCOPPER MAND70LDS.\nCopper manifolds are used for\nwater inlets and outlets in the cir.\nculating system.\nLUBRICATION.\nAutomatic splash, Cadillac exclu\nsive system.\nTRANSMISSION.\nThree speed selective type slid\ning gear.\nDRIVE.\nDirect shaft with two universal\njoints running in oil bath.\nTIRES.\n34ineh by 4.inch.\nSPRINGS.\nSemi-elliptic front, three-quarter\nplatform rear.\nREMOVABLE CLUTCH.\nClutch may be removed in a very\nfew minutes without disturbing\nother members.\ny The von Hamm-Young CoLtdL-\" Sole Agents\nWATERWORKS FIGURES\nFOR FISCAL YEAR\ncon\ndiai! anv\ncentestauts figure in a\nh. v will